 reveal a history of gender diverse individuals that has not been recognised until recently.Taking an interdisciplinary approach these essays will appeal to classicists, ancient historians, archaeologists as well as those working in gender studies, transgender studies, LGBTQ+ studies, anthropology and women’s studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aCivilization, Ancient. 0aGender identityxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aGender identityxHistory. 0aGender-nonconforming peoplexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aSex customsxHistoryyTo 1500. 4aClassics & Ancient History. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh1 aAdkins, Evelyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAgri, Dalida, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAsh, Rowan Emily, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBegum-Lees, Rebecca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeminion, Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDyer, Jennifer, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aDyer, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHughes, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKelly, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCoskey, Denise Eileen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPassaro, Kimberly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPenrose, Walter D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRantala, Jussi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShannon-Henderson, K. E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSowers, Brian P., econtributor.4ctb4https:/